'''Laxman Rao''' is an [[India|Indian]] writer and tea-seller. The author of over 24 [[Hindi literature|novels, plays and political essays]], Rao, a graduate of [[Delhi University]], is also a sidewalk tea-seller in [[Delhi]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/nov/16/books.india</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/newdelhi/a-man-of-his-words/article1-833676.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018082546/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/newdelhi/a-man-of-his-words/article1-833676.aspx |archivedate=2014-10-18 |df= }}</ref> Rao says that his books are based on ideas he gets while interacting with his customers and his writings revolve around their personal struggles. But, unlike Rao who is poor, most of the protagonists in his books are rich and well to do. Reviewers have said that his books "exude a rare sense of honesty and humility" and that his "writings are woven around ground realities of life".<ref>http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/11/25/the-bard-of-the-tea-stall/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0</ref> Rao is also known in Europe, where articles are written about him, e.g. in Germany.<ref>http://www.suedasienbuero.de/index.php/archiv/689-3-4-2014</ref>
